//axhob_operation
{rbtgo_ark_enshrine}

NOTE: This operation enshrines upstream base images into
{gar_service}
as content-addressed, human-readable anchors.
The
{rbtr_director}
submits a Cloud Build job that copies each declared
{rbrv_image_origin}
from its upstream registry to GAR with an anchor tag using
the reliquary skopeo image
(`skopeo copy --all`), preserving the manifest list and all per-platform manifests for multi-platform images.
The anchor results are returned via `buildStepOutputs` and
{rbrv_image_anchor}
is then written back to the vessel regime locally.

NOTE: Enshrine is a pre-build preparation step.
It must be run before
{rbtgo_ark_conjure}
when anchored base images are desired.
Conjure works without anchors (passing ORIGIN through), but anchored images provide reproducibility and air-gap readiness.

NOTE: Enshrine runs on Cloud Build, not the Director's workstation.
No local skopeo installation is required.
The GCB step uses Mason SA ambient credentials via the metadata server for GAR writes.

The enshrine operation:

//axhopt_typed_parameter
{rbrv_sigil}
. *Validate Input Parameters*:
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel provided as first argument
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel contains at least one
{rbrv_image_origin}
declaration (slots 1-3)
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel mode is `conjure` (`RBRV_VESSEL_MODE`)
.. {rbbc_require}
reliquary tool images exist in GAR (HEAD check on `docker:latest` canary)

//axhos_step
. *Submit Enshrine Cloud Build Job*:
.. Compose `builds.create` JSON with:
... Single step using
the reliquary skopeo image
as the builder image (script: `rbgje01-enshrine-copy.sh`)
... `_RBGE_*` substitutions: `_RBGE_GAR_HOST`, `_RBGE_GAR_PATH`, `_RBGE_IMAGE_n_ORIGIN` (n = 1, 2, 3; empty for unused slots). Base images are stored in the shared `enshrine` namespace (`{repo}/enshrine:{anchor}`), not per-vessel.
... Mason SA, private pool, timeout
.. Submit via `builds.create` and wait for completion
.. The GCB step, for each non-empty ORIGIN slot:
... Fetches the raw upstream manifest (`skopeo inspect --raw`) and computes its sha256 digest (`sha256sum` of the raw manifest bytes)
... {rbbc_store}
`<<DIGEST>>` -- the sha256 digest of the upstream manifest (manifest list digest for multi-platform images, single manifest digest for single-platform images)
... Constructs anchor: sanitize full origin string (`:` `/` replaced with `-`), append first 10 hex chars of sha256 digest
... Example: `python:3.11-slim` with `sha256:abc123def4...` produces `python-3.11-slim-abc123def4`
... Copies upstream image to the shared `enshrine` namespace in GAR (`{repo}/enshrine:{anchor}`) using `skopeo copy --all`, transferring the manifest list and all per-platform manifests atomically. The anchor is vessel-independent — multiple vessels sharing the same base image origin share one enshrined artifact.
... {rbbc_require}
copy succeeds -- the anchor tag is now a permanent, content-addressed reference in
{gar_service}
containing all upstream platforms
... Single-platform upstream images are handled identically -- `skopeo copy --all` is a no-op on the platform dimension when only one platform exists
.. Writes JSON anchor results to `/builder/outputs/output` (returned as `buildStepOutputs`)

//axhos_step
. *Extract Anchors and Write Regime*:
.. Read `buildStepOutputs[0]` from the completed build result (base64-decoded JSON)
.. For each slot present in the result:
... Write anchor string to `RBRV_IMAGE_n_ANCHOR` in the vessel's `rbrv.env`

//axhoot_typed_output
{rbrv_image_anchor}
Per-slot anchor string written to the vessel regime.

//axhoc_completion
Successful execution produces anchored base image references in
{gar_service}
(with all upstream platforms preserved) and updates the vessel regime with

//axhob_operation
{rbtgo_ark_conjure}

NOTE: This operation conjures an
{rbtga_ark_image}
in
{rbtgi_repository}
by building a container image from a vessel specification. The
{rbtr_director}
performs the build via
{gcb_service}
using direct `builds.create` API submission.

NOTE: Conjure produces both the `-image` and `-about` artifacts in a single Cloud Build job submitted via `builds.create`.
The about steps (`rbgja01`-`rbgja04`) are embedded via stitch alongside the build steps.
The `-vouch` artifact is created by the subsequent {rbtgo_ark_vouch} pipeline stage (always a separate Cloud Build job).

NOTE: The
{rbtga_hallmark}
is minted locally by the
{rbtr_director}
before submission.
The Director knows the complete artifact tag set before the build begins -- naming authority and verification authority are the same entity.

NOTE: The conjure build job runs on the worker pool selected by the vessel's `RBRV_EGRESS_MODE`: tether pool for vessels needing public internet (e.g., `apt-get` in Dockerfile), airgap pool for vessels with all dependencies enshrined in GAR.
The subsequent {rbtgo_ark_vouch} always runs on the airgap pool regardless of vessel egress mode.

The conjure operation:

//axhopt_typed_parameter
{rbtga_ark}
. *Validate Input Parameters*:
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel provided as first argument
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel contains conjuring configuration (RBRV_CONJURE_DOCKERFILE, RBRV_CONJURE_BLDCONTEXT)

//axhos_step
. *Registry Preflight*:
.. *Reliquary check*: HEAD request to `«RELIQUARY»/docker:latest` manifest in
{gar_service}.
{rbbc_require}
HTTP 200 — on 404, fail with directive to run inscribe first.
The reliquary is a co-versioned set of builder tool images inscribed from upstream into private GAR. Each vessel declares its reliquary; multiple datestamped reliquaries can coexist.
.. *Enshrine check*: For each indexed slot (n = 1, 2, 3) where both
{rbrv_image_origin}
and
{rbrv_image_anchor}
are set:
... HEAD request to `enshrine:«ANCHOR»` manifest in
{gar_service}
... {rbbc_require}
HTTP 200 — on 404, fail with directive to run {rbtgo_ark_enshrine} first.
Multiple vessels sharing the same anchor need only one enshrine.
.. Preflight prevents wasted
{gcb_service}
submission time on missing images, with copy-paste remediation commands

//axhos_step
. *Resolve Base Images*:

//axhob_operation
{rbtgo_ark_kludge}

NOTE: This operation builds a vessel image locally on the workstation using `docker build`, bypassing Cloud Build and GAR entirely. It produces a
{rbtga_hallmark}
with a `k` prefix (kludge) that composes cleanly with the nameplate and compose infrastructure but is obviously not a production hallmark.

NOTE: Kludge is a deliberate development shortcut for fast edit-build-test cycles. It enables iterating on vessel Dockerfiles, entrypoint scripts, and package lists without waiting for a Cloud Build round-trip. The ugly name is intentional -- this is not part of the production hallmark pipeline.

NOTE: The kludge hallmark format is `k«YYMMDDHHMMSS»-«git-describe»`, paralleling conjure's `c«YYMMDDHHMMSS»` and bind's `b«YYMMDDHHMMSS»-r«YYMMDDHHMMSS»`. The timestamp provides chronological sorting; the `git describe --always` suffix ties the image to a specific commit. The dirty-tree guard ensures the describe always corresponds to a committed state. The `k` prefix makes kludge hallmarks visually distinct in nameplate files and `docker image ls` output.

The kludge operation:

//axhopt_typed_parameter
{rbtga_ark}
. *Validate Input Parameters*:
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel provided as first argument (sigil or path)
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel is conjure mode (bind and graft vessels have no local Dockerfile)
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel has conjuring configuration (RBRV_CONJURE_DOCKERFILE, RBRV_CONJURE_BLDCONTEXT)

//axhos_step
. *Resolve Base Images*:
.. For each indexed slot (n = 1, 2, 3) where
{rbrv_image_origin}
is set, use the origin directly as the `RBF_IMAGE_n` build-arg
.. No enshrine anchor resolution -- kludge pulls base images from upstream registries

//axhos_step
. *Assign Kludge Hallmark*:
.. Mint hallmark as `k«YYMMDDHHMMSS»-«git-describe»` from dispatch timestamp and `BURD_GIT_CONTEXT`
.. {rbbc_store}
`«HALLMARK»`

//axhos_step
. *Build Image Locally*:
.. Run `docker build` with resolved `RBF_IMAGE_n` build-args
.. Build for host platform only (no multi-arch -- development builds run where they are built)
.. Tag as `«GAR_BASE»/«SIGIL»:«HALLMARK»-image` to match compose YAML interpolation format

//axhos_step
. *Create Fake Vouch Tag*:
.. `docker tag` the image ref to also carry the `-vouch` suffix
.. This is the same image aliased -- no provenance verification, no DSSE envelope
.. Satisfies the `rbob_charge` vouch gate (`docker image inspect` on vouch ref)

//axhos_step
. *Report Hallmark*:
.. Print the hallmark value for the operator to paste into the nameplate `.env` file
.. Persist hallmark to `BURD_OUTPUT_DIR` for downstream chaining

== Limitations

* Requires GCP depot configuration (foundry kindle validates `RBDC_DIRECTOR_RBRA_FILE` exists, though kludge does not use credentials)
* Host platform only -- a kludge-built `linux/arm64` image on Apple Silicon will not run on `linux/amd64` hosts
* No about artifact, no provenance chain -- the vouch tag is a same-image alias with no attestation content
* Not suitable for release or delivery -- use {rbtgo_ark_conjure} for production hallmarks

